    {
      "type": "grammar",
      "title": "Asking for Directions with 'Di mana' and 'Ke mana'",
      "explanation": "In Indonesian, 'di mana' means 'where (at)' and is used to ask about a location: 'Di mana stasiun?' (Where is the station?). 'Ke mana' means 'where (to)' and is used for destinations: 'Mau ke mana?' (Where do you want to go?). Adding '-nya' to a noun is like adding 'the': 'hotelnya' (the hotel). To give directions, use 'belok' (turn) with 'kiri' (left) or 'kanan' (right), and 'jalan lurus' (go straight). The word 'naik' (ride/take) is used with vehicles: 'naik bus' (take a bus), 'naik taksi' (take a taxi).",
      "examples": [
        {
          "english": "Where is the train station?",
          "target_primary": "Di mana stasiunnya?",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "Where do you want to go?",
          "target_primary": "Mau ke mana?",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "I want to go to the airport.",
          "target_primary": "Saya mau ke bandara.",
          "target_alt": ""
        },
        {
          "english": "Take a taxi to the hotel.",
          "target_primary": "Naik taksi ke hotel.",
          "target_alt": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "cultural_note",
      "title": "Getting Around in Indonesia",
      "content": "Indonesia offers a wide variety of transportation options. In Jakarta, the TransJakarta bus rapid transit system and the MRT (Mass Rapid Transit) are modern and efficient. Ride-hailing apps like Gojek and Grab are extremely popular throughout the country -- you can book cars, motorbike taxis ('ojek'), and even food delivery. In smaller towns, the 'angkot' (short for 'angkutan kota', or city transport) is a common minibus with fixed routes but no fixed stops -- just shout 'Kiri!' (Left!) when you want to get off, and the driver will pull over. Becak (pedicabs) are still found in some cities. Always agree on a fare before getting into an unmetered vehicle, and using apps gives you price transparency."
    }
